00:43:09.990 --> 00:43:15.127
and-- isn't that a
possible scenario?

00:43:15.127 --> 00:43:17.210
STEVE GULLANS: It's certainly
a possible scenario.

00:43:17.210 --> 00:43:19.010
I mean, the way we
see new technologies

00:43:19.010 --> 00:43:21.370
in terms of health
care kinds of systems

00:43:21.370 --> 00:43:24.150
like we're talking about here
is, first you do the obvious.

00:43:24.150 --> 00:43:27.700
You take on tragic
neonatal diseases,

00:43:27.700 --> 00:43:30.260
children born with genetic
problems and things like that.

00:43:30.260 --> 00:43:31.926
In fact, the first
gene therapy was just

00:43:31.926 --> 00:43:34.210
approved three years
ago for an inborn

00:43:34.210 --> 00:43:37.830
error of metabolism for kids.

00:43:37.830 --> 00:43:40.220
From there you move
into older people,

00:43:40.220 --> 00:43:41.852
like cancers and
things like that.

00:43:41.852 --> 00:43:43.310
And that's where
these technologies

00:43:43.310 --> 00:43:44.601
are getting deployed right now.

00:43:44.601 --> 00:43:48.130
And we're at the very dawn
of these technologies having

00:43:48.130 --> 00:43:48.950
an impact.

00:43:48.950 --> 00:43:51.226
But in other aspects
of other things

00:43:51.226 --> 00:43:52.850
