00:51:06.600 --> 00:51:07.266
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:51:07.266 --> 00:51:09.804
Thank you.

00:51:09.804 --> 00:51:11.220
AUDIENCE: So coming
back to random

00:51:11.220 --> 00:51:13.910
versus non-random mutation.

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:16.480
You'll have to excuse my
ignorance in this field,

00:51:16.480 --> 00:51:19.120
but what is the
source of randomness

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:21.432
for the random mutation?

00:51:21.432 --> 00:51:22.890
STEVE GULLANS:
Random mutation-- we

00:51:22.890 --> 00:51:26.910
have three billion GATs and Cs
in a single set of chromosomes

00:51:26.910 --> 00:51:30.290
in a human, and every
time a cell divides--

00:51:30.290 --> 00:51:32.900
and you're filled with
gazillions of cells-- it has

00:51:32.900 --> 00:51:35.120
to make an exact copy of that.

00:51:35.120 --> 00:51:37.290
And that exact copy
is done by enzymes.

00:51:37.290 --> 00:51:40.050
And going from mother
to child there's

00:51:40.050 --> 00:51:43.030
about 100 errors made
in that copying process.

00:51:43.030 --> 00:51:46.450
It's just a stochastic,
as far as we can tell,

00:51:46.450 --> 00:51:49.750
almost random or random
event across the genome.

00:51:49.750 --> 00:51:52.105
And so these are just a
single G or a single T

00:51:52.105 --> 00:51:53.630
or A or C is changed.

00:51:53.630 --> 00:51:56.850
And if it doesn't affect you
functionally you're fine.

00:51:56.850 --> 00:51:59.450
A simple arithmetic
analysis says,

00:51:59.450 --> 00:52:02.620
if there's 7 billion
people on the planet you

00:52:02.620 --> 00:52:04.142
have 3 billion bases of DNA.

00:52:04.142 --> 00:52:05.850
So there's more people
than there is DNA.

00:52:05.850 --> 00:52:07.080
And everybody carries 100.

00:52:07.080 --> 00:52:11.090
That means 700 billion
DNA sequence errors exist.

00:52:11.090 --> 00:52:13.770
So every possible mutation
that you can live with

00:52:13.770 --> 00:52:15.079
exists already on this planet.

00:52:15.079 --> 00:52:17.370
We just have to sequence
everybody to see what's there.

00:52:17.370 --> 00:52:18.786
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
but if the process

00:52:18.786 --> 00:52:21.310
is a purely
mechanical or chemical

00:52:21.310 --> 00:52:23.700
I don't see a source
of randomness there.

00:52:23.700 --> 00:52:26.810
STEVE GULLANS: The
randomness is-- well,

00:52:26.810 --> 00:52:30.337
could make it more frequent
with radiation and other things.

00:52:30.337 --> 00:52:31.420
It's a thermal inactivity.

00:52:31.420 --> 00:52:34.800
It's a mis-recognition
of the perfection.

00:52:34.800 --> 00:52:37.650
The idea is, an enzyme is
looking for a substrate.

00:52:37.650 --> 00:52:40.910
And apparently it gets it
right 99.9% of the time

00:52:40.910 --> 00:52:42.375
in finding the right substrate.

00:52:42.375 --> 00:52:45.000
JUAN ENRIQUEZ: And the nuance in
your article-- in your comment

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:50.110
is important because when
you look at DNA research

00:52:50.110 --> 00:52:53.120
by Ting Wu over at
Harvard is showing

00:52:53.120 --> 00:52:57.220
that there are highly
conserved sequences that

00:52:57.220 --> 00:53:00.010
are common to animals,
that are common to humans,

00:53:00.010 --> 00:53:01.350
that are common to plants.

00:53:01.350 --> 00:53:04.730
So there are certain
pathways, certain genes

00:53:04.730 --> 00:53:07.940
that are common across
various species.

00:53:07.940 --> 00:53:10.380
It means, if you get a
random mutation in that,

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:13.380
likely the animal dies
or the plant dies.

00:53:13.380 --> 00:53:15.100
So some of the sources
of randomness--

00:53:15.100 --> 00:53:17.560
if you get radiation
and the radiation

00:53:17.560 --> 00:53:19.670
hits and splits your
DNA in a certain way,

00:53:19.670 --> 00:53:22.290
if a chemical comes in
and splices your chemical

00:53:22.290 --> 00:53:24.530
in a different way,
if the sun comes in,

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:27.690
if alcohol comes in,
if tobacco comes in,

00:53:27.690 --> 00:53:29.040
if coal smoke comes in.

00:53:29.040 --> 00:53:30.660
So there's a whole
series of things

00:53:30.660 --> 00:53:34.350
that are trying to rip
your DNA apart every day

00:53:34.350 --> 00:53:37.180
and your DNA is continuously
re-stitching and remaking

00:53:37.180 --> 00:53:38.150
itself.

00:53:38.150 --> 00:53:38.650
Right?

00:53:38.650 --> 00:53:42.750
And in a bunch of these places
those cuts are at random.

00:53:42.750 --> 00:53:45.290
If they're cuts at random
in the wrong place,

00:53:45.290 --> 00:53:46.960
the organism will die
and not reproduce.

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:49.820
STEVE GULLANS: You
get cancer, basically.

00:53:49.820 --> 00:53:54.440
AUDIENCE: So if you look at
the DNA as a closed system,

00:53:54.440 --> 00:53:56.770
there's no-- you're
saying there would

00:53:56.770 --> 00:53:59.447
be no sources of
randomness in that case.

00:53:59.447 --> 00:54:01.280
STEVE GULLANS: If it
was 100 percent closed.

00:54:01.280 --> 00:54:04.110
But just a cosmic ray coming
in and hitting the DNA

00:54:04.110 --> 00:54:06.390
can actually cause a
single base to change.

00:54:08.974 --> 00:54:10.140
And that has to be repaired.

00:54:10.140 --> 00:54:11.598
And if it's not
repaired properly--

00:54:11.598 --> 00:54:13.799
and so the point of
living to 100 is,

00:54:13.799 --> 00:54:16.090
this is happening every day,
every second in our bodies

00:54:16.090 --> 00:54:16.970
in every single cell.

00:54:16.970 --> 00:54:18.370
We're trying to correct things.

00:54:18.370 --> 00:54:20.200
It is a very rare event
for these mutations

00:54:20.200 --> 00:54:24.580
to arise because we have so many
redundancies in the pathways.

00:54:24.580 --> 00:54:26.690
Not wholly closed.

00:54:26.690 --> 00:54:28.770
AUDIENCE: So my question
is, what sort of effects

00:54:28.770 --> 00:54:31.880
are humans having on the
random mutation side of things?

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:36.050
Do we see a change in
random mutation rates?

00:54:36.050 --> 00:54:39.954
I mean, I could see things
being radiation or hormones.

00:54:39.954 --> 00:54:42.370
STEVE GULLANS: Well, that was
a piece of the last century.

00:54:42.370 --> 00:54:44.640
I mean, we were not
dummies when we figured out

00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:50.540
that asbestos, radioactivity, a
lot of toxins, DDT, et cetera,

00:54:50.540 --> 00:54:53.880
were causing outbreaks of
cancer and other diseases.

00:54:53.880 --> 00:54:58.570
And so they tended to be organ
specific because the toxin

00:54:58.570 --> 00:54:59.740
would accumulate there.

00:54:59.740 --> 00:55:01.120
Or with radiation.

00:55:01.120 --> 00:55:03.260
Or tended to be in cells
that reproduce quickly

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:06.050
because the DNA was being
repaired all the time--

00:55:06.050 --> 00:55:07.775
or was more likely
to be changing.

00:55:07.775 --> 00:55:10.250
And so as we're aware the
cancers were coming up.

00:55:10.250 --> 00:55:11.750
In terms of it being
random, there's

00:55:11.750 --> 00:55:15.330
only one paper I know that
says that there is something

00:55:15.330 --> 00:55:17.570
about the process
that is not random,

00:55:17.570 --> 00:55:20.180
and it has to do with some
asymmetry about the enzymes.

00:55:20.180 --> 00:55:23.870
But in general people have
described it, since the 1920s

00:55:23.870 --> 00:55:27.800
and since including Mendel's
ideas of genetic units

00:55:27.800 --> 00:55:32.740
or genes, that these are just
absolutely random processes.

00:55:32.740 --> 00:55:35.286
AUDIENCE: Is the amount--
so you said 100 per--

00:55:35.286 --> 00:55:37.535
STEVE GULLANS: Per generation
it ranges from 50 to 400

00:55:37.535 --> 00:55:38.475
in different papers.

00:55:38.475 --> 00:55:39.850
AUDIENCE: Is it
going up or down?

00:55:39.850 --> 00:55:41.430
STEVE GULLANS: Well, that's a
new paper that just came out

00:55:41.430 --> 00:55:43.300
a couple months ago from David
